Anonymous Thu 14 Dec 2023 15:25:23 No.61832167 Report
Quoted By: >>61832191 >>61832266 >>61833364
>>61830170
>>61830170
Why does "Road to the Olympics" read like "Jerk off instructions" instead of a story? There's and excessive amount of italicizing, bolding, and redundancy in notation. Let's take a look at the first paragraph and show you how you can avoid the same mistakes.

>"*That h-human st-stamina of yours is — huff, huff — pretty much CHEATING, dude~!*" your running partner[e6 link] managed to pant out between ragged breaths you didn’t like the sound of in the slightest…
Alright, I get it. You're trying to start with something attention-grabbing so you went with the porn fakeout. Here's the thing: I don't want to be punched in the face by my porn. That's what videos and JOI are for. This is clearly supposed to be a long-form story if you have 6-7 chapters already, so don't spoil my appetite with this. You've gotta build up to the porn.

>muh h-human s-stamina
Might as well carry a neon sign saying "HEY, did you know this is HMOFA?" That's a quick way to ruin the immersion.
>*— huff, huff — pretty much CHEATING, dude~!*
Wait, so the whole sentence is a quote in italics, plus "cheating" is boldfaced, plus there's a hyphen break, plus there's a tilde and an exclamation point at the end? This isn't a Christmas tree man, you don't have to decorate everything so much. First off, the exclamation point makes the tilde redundant. Also the tilde is usually for when a character is half-singing, but if this cheetah girl is out of breath, how could she inflect her voice properly?
(1/3)

Anonymous Thu 14 Dec 2023 15:27:46 No.61832191 Report
Quoted By: >>61832211 >>61833364 >>61837194
>>61832167
>[e6 link]
Another omen of a booru-esc story. Look, it's fine to include pictures in your story, but this example sucks because 1) it's taking me to e6, which is where porn punches me in the face, and 2) more importantly, a picture is worth 1000 words. You just lost the opportunity to describe this cheetah girl in writing because you handed it to us. It would've been so cool if we got to see what she looked like through Anon's eyes first, or even the narrator's eyes. The patterns of the fur, of the warm softness of her look? Anthro Imagery like this is a cornerstone of good hmofa.
For example, there was this one short story with a Sparkledog in it, and as we all know, it's impossible to describe a Sparkledog's fur pattern succinctly. We get a rough idea from the writing, but a full reveal happens later when the protagonist draws a portrait of her in his notebook. The reader gets to see this image as well, and it's a super cool reveal that used multiple media, and I wish more people talked about these types of artistic choices.
>managed to pant out between ragged breaths
Wait, so she's stuttering, and huffing, and additionally you had to tell us that she's panting, specifically with ragged breaths? It's so redundant it feels like a TikTok: There's an actor doing something, and a narration telling you what the actor is doing, and text telling you what the actor is doing, replete with emojis telling you how to feel. Please don't make this a TikTok; you'll lose any form of nuance or subtlety in your writing.
(2/3)

Anonymous Thu 14 Dec 2023 15:29:37 No.61832211 Report
Quoted By:
>>61832191
>ragged breaths you didn’t like the sound of in the slightest…
I personally love the way panting sounds. Don't tell me how I feel. This is one of the problems with 2nd person writing, but if you're clever you'll never have to tell people. Why tell me that the protagonist is embarrassed, when you could show or suggest it to me? Could've said "...ragged breaths that would make a decent man look away." Or "...ragged breaths that tell you to avert your gaze." In second person, you can tell me what I do but you shouldn't tell me how I feel. Because I'm the reader and I know how the event of the story make me feel.
>...
There's no need for an ellipse. The protagonist has finished his thought and the scene hasn't changed.
Did you say this chapter was sanitized? Look, I really do appreciate the fact that you're writing. However, it feels like you're feeding me applesauce with all of these annotations and redundancies. Try to save the bold and italic stuff for the two or three most important sentences in the chapter, or if the emphasis of the sentence is totally ambiguous without it.
